{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ποθ-έω</b>, <br /> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 1.343, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Aeolic dialect</i> <b>ποθήω</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica 23\">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>infinitive</i> ποθήμεναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 12.110 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>imperfect</i> πόθεον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.726, etc.; also ποθέεσκον 1.492, Call.in “PSI” 9.1092.51 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>future</i> ποθήσω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 3.11.3, “Oec.” 8.10, (ἐπι-) 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.93; also ποθέσομαι 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 8.18, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 98a: \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<i>aorist</i> ἐπόθεσα, <i>Epic dialect</i> πόθεσα, <i>infinitive</i> ποθέσαι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.219, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.375, 4.748, (προ-) 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus “Θρασύβουλος - Scripta Minora” 29; ἐπόθησα 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Meno” 84c, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 5.3.20, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; both forms in codices of [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus, ἐπόθησε 3.36, ἐπόθεσαν 9.22 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐπόθεσα also in codices of [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 4.122, 19.7 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> πεπόθηκα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Anthologia Graeca” 11.417, 2nd c.AD: Sextus Empiricus Philosophus “adversus Mathematicos” 11.139, etc.\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]:— <i>middle</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 103 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, <i>perfect</i> πεπόθημαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.AD: Orphica “Hymni” 81.3, etc.: (compare πόθος near the end)\">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]:—<b>long for, yearn after</b> (what is absent), <b>miss</b> or <b>regret</b> (what is lost), φθινύθεσκε.. αὖθι μένων, ποθέεσκε δ᾽ ἀϋτήν τε πτόλεμόν τε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.492; πόθεόν γε μὲν ἀρχόν 2.703; τοίην γὰρ κεφαλὴν ποθέω 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 1.343; π. στρατιᾶς ὀφθαλμὸν ἐμᾶς 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 6.16, compare 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.36, 9.22, etc.; ἄνδρας πόλις ἥδε ποθεῖ “IG” 12.945.10; ποθεῖν ποθοῦντα τήνδε γῆν στρατὸν λέγεις 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 545; τὸν δ᾽ ἐμὸν δῆμον ποθῶν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 33; ποθεῖς τὸν οὐ παρόντα [prev. author] “Pl.” 1127; αἱ κνῆμαι.. σου.. τὰς πέδας π. [prev. work] 276 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἡ χώρα αὐτὴ τὸ μὴ ὂν ποθήσει the place itself <b>will miss</b> what is absent, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Oeconomicus” 8.10; π. τὰς ἐν τῇ νεότητι ἡδονάς 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 329a, compare “Ti.” 19a, 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.70 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 632, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὦ ποθουμένη (i.e. Εἰρήνη) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Pax” 586; ποθεῖκαὶ ποθεῖται 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 255d. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> of things, <b>crave, require,</b> τί γὰρ π. τράπεζ; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 467; π. ἡ ἀπόκρισις ἐρώτησιν τοιάνδε 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 204d, compare “Prt.” 352a. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> with <i>infinitive</i>, <b>to be anxious</b> to do, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 1020, 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 5.64, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 6.4.8 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὸ νοσοῦν ποθεῖ σε ξυμπαραστάτην λαβεῖν my sickness <b>needs</b> to take thee.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 675 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἆρα ἔτι ποθοῦμεν μὴ ἱκανῶς δεδεῖχθα; <b>do we</b> still <b>feel</b> that it has not been satisfactorily proved? [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 896a:\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] —<i>passive</i>, ποθεῖται.. λεχθῆναι <b>requires</b> to be stated, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1097b23. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <i>absolutely</i>, <b>love with fond regret,</b> οἱ δὲ ποθεῦντες ἐν ἤματι γηράσκουσι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 12.2, compare 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Im.” 22, etc. \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> τὸ ποθοῦν <b>longing, desire</b> (wrongly explained by [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Scholia as ={τὸ ποθούμενον}), 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 196. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.3</b></Level3> <i>middle</i> only in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 103 (Lyric poetry), ποθουμένα φρήν the \">Refs</a>]<b>longing</b> soul,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare 12th c.AD: Eustathius Episcopus Thessalonicensis 806.56. \">Refs</a>]","strongNumber":"G8829","accentedUnicode":"ποθέω","shortDef":"to feel absence","mediumDef":"to feel absence","stepGloss":"to feel absence","stepTransliteration":"potheō","count":0,"_step_Type":"verb"}]}